This cleanup session exposed two concrete local footguns.

1. Git hooks inherit repo-local environment like GIT_DIR and GIT_WORK_TREE. When pre-commit launched the nested git-based test suite without clearing those vars, temporary test repos accidentally targeted the outer checkout. Fix: clear `git rev-parse --local-env-vars` before running nested git tests from hooks.

2. A temporary git worktree plus a canonical-looking local path created split-brain state: the place that looked like the repo was not the active checkout, while the active checkout lived elsewhere. This made it too easy to say 'landed' when changes were only local and only checked out in the side worktree. Preference: use jj workspaces over git worktrees for parallel local work in this repo, and keep one obvious working path when possible.

Meta-learning: when local git state gets weird, stop, inspect `git worktree list`, branch refs, hook env, and remotes before doing more surgery.
